english:
  title: Memorial Requesting Retirement in the Year Dingyou
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have reached the age when retirement should be sought, and I humbly beg to be released from my administrative duties.

    That the aged do not withdraw—can this truly reflect my lifelong wish? The times have not permitted it, yet I have lingered long in this exalted station. Only now do I submit this memorial, and I bow in shame and trepidation.

    I confess: throughout my life I have been dull to the demands of the times, clinging only to my own inadequacy. In my earlier years in service, I seemed but a stone sinking into the abyss. Yet encountering this enlightened court, I rose as if riding the wind itself. I have passed through the crucial offices and risen to the helm of state. My body has taken the seat of the highest minister, yet I have never mastered the art of discourse on governance, nor brought glory to the realm through learning. I bear the name of a Confucian official, yet my greatest failing is that I have not illuminated the nation through culture. I merely consume my stipend and feed my family—perhaps this satisfies my own interest, but what service does it render the world?

    Being thus useless, I have again reached the time to request retirement. How could I cling to honor and draw upon myself the reproach of blocking the path of worthy men? Last year I submitted such a request, yet Your Majesty's benevolent heart was reluctant to dismiss it. You sent an imperial messenger to convey your words of comfort, and I was ashamed that my humble station should trouble you with such solicitude. Bound by your command, I have reluctantly remained in office. Yet I fear that if this precedent is now abandoned, all will mock me, and I shall have no face to show.

    Now infirmity and old age press upon me greatly; even walking causes me pain. Though I wish to steel myself, how can I endure? I humbly beseech you: with your boundless compassion and vast forbearance, perceive my dread of public censure and consider my repeated petitions across two years. Grant me leave to retire to my village. Then, like a fish released to swim in waters free, I shall find sufficient joy; like a bird that returns to its nest, I shall at last find rest.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a formal petition (pyo, 表) submitted to the ruler, a traditional East Asian governmental document expressing loyalty while making a request.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Kyubo (1168-1241) was a prominent Korean scholar-official of the Goryeo dynasty, known for his literary talents and service to multiple rulers.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of the fish and bird at the end carries Confucian and Daoist undertones about knowing when to withdraw from public life and return to one's natural state.
